        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator setup provides three high spectral resolution windows centered on the 12CO, 13CO, and C18O 2-1 lines as these provide the best diagnostics of the gas content in disks. We use spectral averaging in order to lower the data rate while still maintaining sufficiently high spectral velocity resolution to resolve the lines and study disk kinematics. 

We also have two broad basebands to measure the continuum emission. These are separated from each other by almost 18 GHz to improve the image fidelity and provide some spectral index information. The LSB continuum window contains the potentially detectable 3-2 transitions of DCO+ and DCN, which can trace the presence of cold gas and CO snowlines (Mathews et al., 2013, A&amp;A, 557, 132), therefore we use moderate spectral resolution (1.5 km/s) for this baseband.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have chosen a combination of angular resolution and maximum recoverable scale that can be achieved in a single array configuration (C36-6) without requiring non-standard observing modes (i.e., maximum baselines &lt; 2 km). At the distance of our target (~450 pc), this resolution will allow us to study disk structures down to ~30 AU radius scales, which includes rings and asymmetries expected in transition disks. The largest angular scale corresponds to ~900 AU, thus we expect to maintain sensitivity to the full disk based on our ~400 AU upper limit to the diameter of the dust distribution of the disk (see inset of Figure 2a in proposal).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The line sensitivity corresponds to an estimated 5-sigma detection of the expected 13CO line emission per beam from the disk (based on the peak flux of our previous 12CO line detection). This will allow us to trace the radially averaged gas distribution in the disk down to Saturn masses, as shown by the models in Williams &amp; Best (2014, ApJ, 778, 59). The corresponding continuum sensitivity will allow us to detect any dust vorticies in the disk down to sub-Earth masses. These sensitivities are better than most ALMA observations published to date of the dust and gas distributions in circumstellar disks. We observe at high spectral resolution because we can integrate in velocity without losing sensitivity, while also preserving the ability to study disk kinematics. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
