    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe the circumstellar disk around the Herbig Ae star HD 245185, a puzzling object that appears to be in the short-lived stage of final disk dispersal and terrestrial planet formation. Our previous observations of HD 245185 support this interpretation: the disk has an anomalously large dust mass for its age, yet very highly depleted gas content, while also showing signs of ongoing accretion. The spectral energy distribution is also consistent with a transition disk, which indicates gaps in the disk structure, possibly from planet formation. The high resolution and sensitivity of ALMA Cycle 3 can resolve sub-Earth dust vorticies and constrain radially averaged gas distributions to sub-Saturn masses. These observations of the late stages of disk clearing will be crucial to understanding how disks evolve to form planetary systems.</prp:abstract>
